Read the given passage and answer the questions given below:

Good monsoon may have laid the foundation for record foodgrain production, but it was the launch of schemes like PM-Kisan that has set the ball rolling for structural reforms in the agriculture sector to achieve the target of doubling farmers’ income.
The Centre’s focus in 2019, continued to be ‘kisan kalyan’ (farmers’ welfare) in the second term of the Modi administration and the policy changes were as per the recommendations by the Dalwai Committee for doubling farmers’ 2015-16 income level, in real terms, by 2022.
Not only the budget allocation for the sector was hiked over 78% to ₹1.39 lakh crore for the current fiscal, the government persuaded states to adopt long pending agri-marketing reforms as per the Model Agriculture Produce and Livestock Market Committee (APML) Act.
Besides, it tweaked some existing schemes for promoting quick transfer of new farm technology and facilitate agri-exports by allowing treatment of Methylcyclopropene (MCP) for enhancing the shelf life of fresh fruits and vegetables among others.
To mitigate severe agrarian distress, the government launched a new agri-scheme the Pradhan Mantri Kisan Samman Nidhi (PM-Kisan), just before the Lok Sabha polls, with an aim to provide direct cash benefit of ₹6,000 annually to each of 14 crore farmers. Later it also unvieled an old age pension scheme the Pradhan Mantri Kisan Maan-Dhan Yojana.
“By and large the government’s priority was on improving the farmers’ income and accordingly the schemes were framed and some existing ones were tweaked to achieve this objective,” Agriculture Minister Narendra Singh Tomar told PTI in an interview.
Asserting that several of the Dalwai Committee’s recommendations are being implemented, the Minister said, “the work is in progress, the results will be visible soon.”

On foodgrain production, the Minister said despite delayed but good monsoon, untimely rains in some states like Maharasthra and Karnataka affected some kharif (summer) crops, the country’s overall foodgrain output is expected to be better and most likely will surpass 281.37 million tonne achieved in 2018-19 crop year (July-June).

The prospect of rabi (winter) crops like wheat are “extremely” good because of better soil moisture and good weather conditions, he said.
Mr. Tomar, however, noted that the country is self-sufficient in many commodities and the government’s policy has shifted from production-centric to farmers’ income centric.
The government has set a production target of 291.1 million tonnes of foodgrain in 2019-20 crop year (July-June). Already kharif (summer) crops have been harvested, the sowing of rabi (winter) crops is coming to end soon.
According to experts, the year was no doubt “better” in terms of prices that farmers got for their produce when compared to last two years even though the rising food inflation was a concern with retail onion prices touching the peak of ₹200/kg last month due to estimated 25% fall in kharif output of the key kitchen staple, they said.

Mr. Tomar, however, noted that the country is self-sufficient in many commodities and the government’s policy has shifted from production-centric to farmers’ income centric.
The government has set a production target of 291.1 million tonnes of foodgrain in 2019-20 crop year (July-June). Already kharif (summer) crops have been harvested, the sowing of rabi (winter) crops is coming to end soon.
According to experts, the year was no doubt “better” in terms of prices that farmers got for their produce when compared to last two years even though the rising food inflation was a concern with retail onion prices touching the peak of ₹200/kg last month due to estimated 25% fall in kharif output of the key kitchen staple, they said.

Q 51
Report Bookmark

Given below are five answer figures. Which of these five answer figures should come after the problem figures, if the sequence was continued?​


Solution

The pattern followed by the four elements in the corners is - clockwise rotation and swapping of diagonally opposite elements. In the last figure the elements have been swapped. Hence, we need to rotate these elements in clockwise manner to get the answer figure. The two semicircles in the left half rotate by 90 degrees clockwise in each figure. Hence, in the answer figure they should be facing right and up respectively. The two semicircles on the right rotate by 90 degrees counter-clockwise every two moves. As they did not rotate in the last move, they should rotate now. Hence, both should face upwards. Hence, option C.

Q 52
Report Bookmark

Given below are five answer figures. Which of these five answer figures should come after the problem figures, if the sequence was continued?

Solution

The star always moves two steps (one step is half side) in anti-clockwise direction in even tiles. The letter P moves 3 steps in clockwise direction in each even tile. Hence, in the answer figure, P should be in the bottom row in the middle. The star should be in the top-right corner. Hence, the answer is figure (4).

Raju and Soniya started their journey from Jaipur to Delhi and Delhi to Jaipur respectively in the opposite directions towards each other and the distance between Delhi to Jaipur is 329 km. The speed of Raju and Soniya is 44km/hr and 63 km/hr. Soniya started her journey after 1 hr of Raju's start time and after an hour Soniya reduced 5/7th of her speed.So, time taken by them to meet?


Solution

Distance = 329 km
Speed of Raju =44 km/hr
Speed of Soniya = 63km/hr

Distance covered by Soniya in 1 hr = 63 km

After 2 hr, relative speed = 44 + 45 = 89 km/hr
Remaining distance = 329 - 151 = 178 km
Time taken with reduced speed = 178/89 = 2 hr
Total time taken to meet each other = 2 + 2 = 4 hr

Mukesh bought a certain article at a certain price. He marked up the price of the article by certain percentage. Suresh comes to buy that article from Mukesh. Mukesh offers him a discount of 40 %. However, Suresh is not willing to pay that much. Hence, Mukesh offers another discount of 25 % and sells it to Suresh. If Mukesh made a profit of 1200 in this transaction, then what was the mark-up percentage?


Solution

Let the cost price of the article be 100x. Let the mark up percentage be ‘m’. Hence, the marked price will be 100x + mx. Now, the discount which is being offered is 40 % and then another 25 %. Hence, the effective discount will be 40 + 25 - 40*25/100 = 55%
Hence, the selling price will be .45 times the marked price. Thus, selling price will be
.45(10x0 + mx) = 45x + .45mx
=> We know that
45x - .45mx - 100x = 1200
From this, we can see that we have two variables in this equation. So we cannot uniquely determine the value of ‘m’. Thus, option e is the correct answer.

Q 98
Report Bookmark

Pipe A can individually fill a tank in 16 hours. Pipe B has double the efficiency of Pipe A. A drain pipe C can empty the tank in 12 hours. In the first hour, A and B are opened, in the second hour, B and C are opened and in the third hour A and C are opened and so on until the tank is 83.33% full. After that, only pipe B is opened. In how much time will the tank be completely filled?


Solution

Given, A can fill the tank in 16 hours.
B has double the efficiency of A and hence B can fill the tank in half of the time taken by A.
B can fill the tank in 8 hours.
C can empty the tank in 12 hours.
Let the capacity of the tank be 48 units.(LCM of 16, 8 and 12)
Efficiency of A = 48/16 = 3 units per hour
Efficiency of B = 48/8 = 6 units per hour.
Efficiency of C = 48/12 = -4 units per hour.
A and B are opened in first hour.
Capacity of the tank filled in the first hour = 6+3 = 9 units.
B and C are opened in second hour.
Capacity of the tank filled in the second hour = 6-4 = 2 units.
A and C are opened in third hour.
Capacity of the tank emptied in the third hour = 3-4 = -1 unit.

Hence, in three hours, 9+2-1 = 10 units of the tank will be filled.
This is repeated until the tank is 83.33% full.
83.33% = 56\dfrac{5}{6}65​
83.33% of 48 = 56×48=40\dfrac{5}{6}\times48 = 4065​×48=40 units.
To fill 10 units of tank, it takes 3 hours.
Then, 30 units will be filled in 9 hours.
Next 9 units of tank will be filled by A and B in 1 hour.
Total 39 units of tank will be filled in 10 hours.
B and C can fill 2 units of tank in 1 hour.
Then, 1 unit of tank will be filled in 0.5 hours or 30 minutes.
Then, 40 units of tank will be filled in 10 hours 30 minutes.

Now, Only B is opened.
Remaining capacity = 48 - 40 = 8 units.
B can fill the tank at 6 units per hour.
Then, 8 units of the tank will be filled by B in 86hours=86×60=80\dfrac{8}{6} hours = \dfrac{8}{6}\times60 = 8068​hours=68​×60=80 minutes.
Therefore, Total tank will be filled in 10 hours 30 minutes + 80 minutes = 11 hours 50 minutes.

Q 100
Report Bookmark

Two trains A and B depart at the same time from Chennai towards Mumbai. Train A travels to Mumbai through Bangalore. Bangalore is 300 kms away from Chennai and 1000 Km away from Mumbai. Train B travels to Mumbai through Hyderabad. Hyderabad is 650 Kms away from Mumbai and 750 Kms away from Hyderabad. Train B travels with a constant speed of 100 kmph. If train A travels from Chennai to Bangalore at 50 kmph, at what speed must it travel from Bangalore to Mumbai provided both the trains reach Mumbai at the same time?


Solution

Total distance to Mumbai via Hyderabad = 650+750 = 1400 Km.
Total distance to Mumbai via Bangalore = 1000 + 300 = 1300 km.
Train B travels at a constant speed of 100 kmph. This means that train B will take 1400/100 = 14 hours to reach Mumbai.
Train A must also take 14 hours.
It travels from Chennai to Bangalore at 50 kmph. 300/50 = 6 hours.
Train A must complete the remaining journey in 14 - 6 = 8 hours.
Train A will cover 1000 kms in 8 hours at 1000/8 = 125 kmph.

A shopkeeper buys some coffee and chicory. The cost price of coffee is 1.5 times the cost price of chicory. He mixes coffee and chicory in some ratio. He makes a profit of 20% by selling the mixture at the cost price of coffee. What is the ratio in which chicory and coffee was mixed by the shop keeper?


Solution

Let us assume the price of chicory to be P.
Price of coffee = 1.5p
Let us assume that coffee and chicory are mixed in the ratio x:y.
We know that he sells the mixture at the cost price of coffee and realises a profit of 20%.
=> Profit = 1.5p(x+y) - 1.5px - py = 0.5py
Cost = 1.5px + py
Profit %age = 0.5py/(1.5px+py)
0.5y/(1.5x + y) = 0.2
0.5y = 0.3x + 0.2y
0.3x = 0.3y
x/y = 1:1

Therefore, option E is the right answer.

Find the ratio between the total time taken by the boat in covering the downstream distance on Monday and Tuesday together and the time taken by the boat in covering the distance in upstream on Wednesday and Thursday taken together?


Solution

On Monday the boat covers 280km in downstream and on Tuesday it covers 450km
so, the time taken by the boat on Monday to cover 280km i.e. from chart speed of boat and speed of current = 12 and 2km/hr respectively
time taken by the boat = 280/14 = 20hours.
Similarly, on Tuesday time taken by the boat to cover 450 km = 450/15 =30 hours
On Wednesday time taken by the boat to cover upstream distance of 180km i.e. speed of the boat and current = 13.5 and 4.5 km/hr respectively i.e. upstream speed = 13.5-4.5 =9km/hr
So, the time taken by the boat = 180/9 = 20 hours
On Thursday the time taken by the boat to cover upstream distance of 430 km i.e.speed of the boat and current = 15 and 5 km/hr respectively i.e. upstream speed = 15-5 =10km/hr
So, the time taken by the boat = 430/10 = 43 hours
so, the required ratio = (20+30):(20+43)
50:63

Hence, option a is the correct answer.

Q 123
Report Bookmark

Is x a positive integer with perfect square number?
I) x<5,x>0
II) x is an even natural number
III) x2−16=0x^{2} - 16 = 0x2−16=0


Solution

From I, 0<x<5 which is sufficient to say that x is positive but not sufficient to say x is a perfect square number.
From II, x is an even natural number which is not sufficient to say that x is a perfect square number.
From III, x2−16=0x^2-16=0x2−16=0 => x2=16=>x=±4x^2=16 => x=\pm4x2=16=>x=±4. Hence, we cannot say that x is positive number.

From I and II, 0<x<5 and x is even natural number. Then, x can be either 2 or 4. Hence, we cannot say that x is a perfect square number.
From II and III, x2−16=0x^2-16=0x2−16=0 => x2=16=>x=±4x^2=16 => x=\pm4x2=16=>x=±4. Since x is an even natural number, x is always positive. Hence, From II and III, we can say that x is positive and perfect square number.
From I and III, x2−16=0x^2-16=0x2−16=0 => x2=16=>x=±4x^2=16 => x=\pm4x2=16=>x=±4. Since 0 < x < 5, x = 4 which is positive and perfect square number.
Therefore, From Either I and II or II and III, we can say that x is positive and perfect square number.

Q 137
Report Bookmark

Who among the following is the tallest?


Solution

In the given statement A is shorter than only 3 persons and he does not like white/Yellow. So, he will like either Black/Blue/Orange/Red.

Also, given in the statement D likes Black. So, A will like either Blue/orange/red.

But E likes red as given. Hence we will have A will like either Blue/orange.

It is also given that the persons who like Red and yellow are of the same heights. Also, given E likes red and is not the shortest.

C is taller than E.

The tallest person's height is 200 cm and is not equal to any other person’s height.

So,  we will have 2 cases for A here.

Case 1:

A likes Blue

______  > _____=   E    >   A   > ____ >_____
 200cm   Yellow    Red     Blue

D likes Black and is taller than F. B is taller than D and F but not the tallest. So, the only possibility that we will get here is as follows.

     C  >   B     =   E   >   A   >    D     >    F

200cm Yellow    Red    Blue     Black     Orange

Given the person who likes orange is neither the shortest or the tallest. Hence this case gets rejected.

Case 2:

A likes Orange

    C      >   E    = ______  >    A        > ______ >_____                

200cm     Red      Yellow     Orange

D likes Black and is taller than F. B is taller than D and F but not the tallest. So, the only possibility that we will get here is as follows.

    C      >   E    =     B      >    A        >  D      >  F

200cm     Red      Yellow     Orange     Black  

So, the only colours left are blue and white. So, we get the final arrangement as follows.

    C      >   E    =     B      >    A        >  D      >  F

200cm     Red      Yellow     Orange     Black     White/Blue

Blue/White

Hence C will be the tallest person.

Q 142
Report Bookmark

How many persons are there between the persons who have the highest number of coins and the least number of coins when counted to the right of the one who has the highest number of coins?


Solution

E has the third highest number of coins and sits third to the right of I. The one who has the highest number of coins sits fifth to the left of I. Here, There will be two possibilities.

G sits to the immediate left of K who has 14 coins. K sits to the immediate right of the one who is opposite to E.

C sits second to the right of L who is not an immediate neighbour of E. Here, There will be two more possibilities.

C sits third to the right of B who is an immediate neighbour of F.
Here, Possibilities I(A) and II(A) can be eliminated since C cannot be to the third right of B.

H sits opposite to D who has third least number of coins. H is not an immediate neighbour of E. F has double the number of coins of D.

A has 19 coins and faces inside but is not an immediate neighbour of E.
Hence, Possibility II(B) can be eliminated.
Remaining person is J.

The one who has the second lowest number of coins sits to the immediate right of the one who has the highest number of coins. The one who has the second highest number of coins sits fourth to the right of the one who has the lowest number of coins.
Here, The one who has 6 coins is to the immediate right of the one who has 32 coins.
The one who has 28 coins is 4th to the right of the one who has 4 coins.

The ratio between the number of coins with L and I is 6:7. In the given numbers, 12, 18 and 21 are left.
Here, 18 and 21 are in the ratio 6:7.
Hence, L has 18 coins and I has 21 coins.
Remaining is C who has 12 coins.

Therefore, The final arrangement is as shown above.
Here, There are 8 people between G who has the highest number of coins and H who has the least number of coins when counted to the right of G.

P%Q : P is equal to Q
P&Q : P is smaller than Q
P=Q : P is greater than or equal to Q

Instructions

Below is given a passage followed by several possible inferences which can be drawn from the facts stated in the passage. You have to examine each inference separately in the context of the passage and decide upon its degree of truth or falsity.

Robert McKenna spent more than two decades with the New York City Police Department, but he has no trouble remembering the days and nights of late May 1979, when much of the city was consumed by the disappearance of a 6-year-old Manhattan boy who had gone missing while headed to school alone for the first time. McKenna, then a patrol officer, was one of a small army of officers knocking on doors in the SoHo neighborhood, shining flashlights behind dumpsters, questioning potential witnesses.

McKenna said he has particularly vivid memories of the bodega that stood on the corner of Prince Street and West Broadway, where the boy's school bus stop was also located. The police had been told that the boy, Etan Patz, might have stopped at the bodega to buy a soda that morning.

"There was a register at the front of the store, a refrigerator full of soda in the back and a wide open floor," McKenna recalled.

McKenna said the bodega served as something of a command post for the police department's search. And he remembers talking with a female officer who had searched the bodega's basement.

"She was a mother of two, I believe, so she was very concerned about this little boy," McKenna said in an interview this week. "She told me she'd checked everywhere, every nook and cranny of the basement."

Nearly 36 years after Etan Patz vanished, a former clerk at the SoHo bodega was tried on charges that he committed the boy's murder. Pedro Hernandez, 18 years old in 1979, confessed in 2012 to having strangled the boy in the store's basement, packed him up in a box and tossed the boy's book bag behind a refrigerator. The trial ended with a hung jury, a dozen people who spent 18 days unsuccessfully trying to reach unanimity. When State Supreme Court Justice Maxwell Wiley formally declared a mistrial on May 8, the jury was split 11-1 for conviction.

In interviews with reporters for New York newspapers and television stations, jurors described long debates about a range of issues that had come up during the trial: whether someone could be convicted on the basis of a confession alone; whether a convicted pedophile who had long been considered the chief suspect in the case was the more likely killer; whether Hernandez, as his lawyers had maintained, was severely mentally ill, and his confession an imagined fiction.

The debates, the jurors, said, also included lengthy discussion of the bodega, and whether it had been properly searched. If it had, wouldn't the police have found the book bag?

Adam Sirois, the lone holdout juror in favor of acquittal, said the debate about the bodega became heated.

"It doesn't add up that they wouldn't have found that bag," Sirois said in an interview with the New York Post. He added, "You almost have to want him to be guilty, in my opinion, to say the police could not have searched the bodega basement. It's right at the bus stop where he was headed. "

In an interview Wednesday with ProPublica, Sirois repeated his bafflement.
"If you believe that they didn't search the bodega top to bottom, then it's just not rational," he said.

McKenna did not testify at the trial. But he had told a version of his account to ProPublica in 2013 and it was included in an extensive examination of the case against Hernandez.
Source: Joaquin Sapien, Propublica

Q 170

ACE:ZXV :: BDF:?

Study the following instructions and answer the questions that follow:

A family consists of eight persons - L, M, N, O, P, Q, R, S across two generations. They are born in different years - 1947, 1951, 1952, 1956, 1984, 1986, 1992, 1995 but not necessarily in the same order. All the ages are calculated on the base year 2019. There are only two couples in the family which is spread across two generations. Each couple has two children.
N is younger than her brother. The difference between the ages of O and her nephew is 15 less than that of M and his only son. S and Q are siblings and the former is older than the latter.  R is the only son of L. O is four years younger than her husband. Q and L are of the same gender. P was born in 1951. Q is the youngest. M is five years younger than his brother-in-law. L is not the husband of O. S is older than N. L is at least 63 years old.

Q 188
Report Bookmark

How is the person born in 1952 related to the person born in 1986?


Solution

P was born in 1951. Q is the youngest.

O is four years younger than her husband. M is five years younger than his brother-in-law. Here, M, O and his brother-in-law can placed as shown below. L is at least 63 years old. Hence, L was born in 1947. Since he is the oldest, he will be male.

S and Q are siblings. Q and L are of same gender. R is the only son of L. The difference between the ages of O and her nephew is 15 less than that of M and his only son. L is not the husband of O. Here, we can say that R and N are brother and sister and Q and S are brother and sister.  Since, L is male, M's brother-in-law will be L. O will be sister of L. Remaining person P will be wife of L. 

Therefore, Final Blood relation is as shown above.
Given, O - R = M - Q - 15
M - O = Q - R + 15
Here, M - O = 4
4 = Q - R + 15
⇒ R - Q = 11
Hence, R is 11 years older than Q

S is older than N.

Therefore, The final arrangement is as shown above.

Here, M was born in 1952 and S was born in 1986.
Hence, M is the father of S.

Q 196
Report Bookmark

How many floors are present between the floors owned by A and G ?


Solution

First draw a table having floor numbers in the first column and no of flats,owner and name of the flat in other columns as shown in the figure.

By writing down all the conditions given we have that the floor owned by E has 3 flats and C has 2 flats and also only C and G can be in 1st floor because it is given that F is an even numbered floor,E lives above F and so it can’t be,B doesn’t live in 1st or 4th floor,also given A doesn’t live in 1st floor, D also lives in even numbered floor and so only C and G can be in 1st floor.Given that the floor below the one owned by E has its name as Patel. Using these conditions we have .

When C is in the 1st floor F should be in 4th floor and E in 5th floor and so A should be in 1st floor both  C and A cannot be 1st floor and so C can’t be in 1st floor and only possibility is G in 1st floor.

C and F has 2 floors between them and so C will be in 5th floor.The floor owned by B is not the 1st and 4th and so the leftover is 2nd floor.Given floor owned by D is named as Singh and above it is Nehru and also given Bose is named for an even numbered floor and only one left is 6th floor and so it is named as Bose.

7 flats are present in odd numbered floor and so only one left is 1st floor and so it has 7 flats.

Floor comprising of 5 flats is present below B and so 4th floor has 5 flats.

Given that Azad is not named for floor owned by A and E and so it is named for G

Also given the floor owned by A is not named as Tagore and so it is named as Gandhi and the only floor left unnamed is E and so it is named as Tagore.

Number of floors present is 5.

There are seven floors in building where first floor is numbered 1,each floor has different number of flats from 1 to 7 not in this order,each floor has an owner namely A,B,C,D,E,F and G not in this order and also each floor is given a name from Gandhi, Nehru, Bose, Azad, Tagore, Singh and Patel not in this order.

1.The name of the floor which D owns has Singh as its name and it is even numbered floor.
2.The floor owned by E has 3 flats and it is immediately above the floor owned by F which is even numbered floor.
3.1st floor has 7 flats in it and 2 flats are present in an odd numbered floor.
4.The floor above the ones which has owner as D is named as Nehru and two floors are present between the floors owned by C and F.
5.The floor owned by E doesn’t have its name as Azad. The flat owned by B is not present in 1st and 4th floor.
6.The name of the floor which A owns doesn’t have Tagore and Azad as its name and it is not the first floor which he owns.
7.The floor which has 1 flat is present just below the floor owned by E and floor which has 5 flats is present below the floor which is owned by B.
8.The floor which has Bose as its name is not an odd numbered floor.
9.The floor owned by A has 6 flats and between it and E three floors are present.
10. The floor which has 1 flat is named as Patel.

Q 200
Report Bookmark

The floor in which 6 flats are present is


Solution

First draw a table having floor numbers in the first column and no of flats,owner and name of the flat in other columns as shown in the figure.

By writing down all the conditions given we have that the floor owned by E has 3 flats and C has 2 flats and also only C and G can be in 1st floor because it is given that F is an even numbered floor,E lives above F and so it can’t be,B doesn’t live in 1st or 4th floor,also given A doesn’t live in 1st floor, D also lives in even numbered floor and so only C and G can be in 1st floor.Given that the floor below the one owned by E has its name as Patel. Using these conditions we have .

When C is in the 1st floor F should be in 4th floor and E in 5th floor and so A should be in 1st floor both  C and A cannot be 1st floor and so C can’t be in 1st floor and only possibility is G in 1st floor.

C and F has 2 floors between them and so C will be in 5th floor.The floor owned by B is not the 1st and 4th and so the leftover is 2nd floor.Given floor owned by D is named as Singh and above it is Nehru and also given Bose is named for an even numbered floor and only one left is 6th floor and so it is named as Bose.

7 flats are present in odd numbered floor and so only one left is 1st floor and so it has 7 flats.

Floor comprising of 5 flats is present below B and so 4th floor has 5 flats.

Given that Azad is not named for floor owned by A and E and so it is named for G

Also given the floor owned by A is not named as Tagore and so it is named as Gandhi and the only floor left unnamed is E and so it is named as Tagore.

6 flats are present in 7th floor.
